= lesson 29: intermission 3

You've learned 131 words, and all the important grammar! So what now?

#strong[Join a Toki Pona community!] #link(
  "https://discord.gg/6zkugJFU4x",
)[ma pona] and #link("https://discord.gg/ChC6qtVsSE")[kama sona] are great
places to find people to talk to, and to practice. You can even #link(
  "https://vrc.group/TOKI.9663",
)[hang out in VRChat]!

#strong[Stay informed!] Every two-four weeks we post a #link(
  "https://sin-kulupu.pona.la/",
)[newsletter] about new things happening. Sign up so you don't miss cool events,
like the #link("https://suno.pona.la/")[24 hour celebration stream] we have
every August!

#strong[Listen to spoken Toki Pona!] #link(
  "https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLjOmpMyMxd8Qs2mAXcLk817tQy_AQj09u",
)[kalama sin] is a podcast where you can listen to live conversations between
proficient Toki Pona speakers. Turn on subtitles if it's difficult to keep up!

#strong[Read more Toki Pona!]
#link("https://raacz.neocities.org/toki-pona/beginner-material")[Practice] by
reading \~70 short stories by jan Lakuse. #link("https://liputenpo.org/")[lipu
  tenpo] publishes a new zine every month or two, with short stories and talks.

And finally, #strong[listen to #link("https://kute.pona.la/")[Toki Pona music]!]
We have lots of talented musicians writing original songs or translating songs
they love. Let's check out this awesome song #emph['ale li ante'] by jan
Nikoleta (kqa)!

